{{italic title}} The phrase '''''NASCAR dad''''' broadly refers to a [[demographic]] group of often white, usually middle-aged, working-class or lower-middle-class men in [[North America]]. The group received this nickname because they are men who are believed to typically enjoy watching [[NASCAR]] racing, or comparable high-impact sports or entertainment.
The term was often used during the [[United States presidential election, 2004|United States presidential election of 2004]], particularly in describing the efforts of [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] to regain the votes of white southern males. The group consists of an estimated 45 million people in the USA.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/rpm/news/story?id=1735251 NASCAR Dads could provide swing vote. ESPN. Retrieved on 2009-01-07]</ref>
