{{Infobox person |name = Sunaura Taylor |image = |birth_date = 1982 |birth_place = [[Tucson, Arizona]] |death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | death_place = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | nationality = | residence = | education = |website = http://sunaurataylor.org/ }}
'''Sunaura "Sunny" Taylor''' (born March 21, 1982) is an [[United States|American]] painter and activist for [[Disability rights movement|disability]] and [[animal rights]]. She currently resides in [[Oakland, California|Oakland]], [[California]], and has taught classes at the [[University of California, Berkeley]].
Taylor's work has been displayed in the [[Smithsonian]] and in other important galleries across the United States.<ref>[http://www.vsarts.org/x951.xml VSA Arts schedule for ''Driving Force''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061001201324/http://www.vsarts.org/x951.xml |date=2006-10-01 }}</ref> She is the recipient of a 2008 Joan Mitchell Foundation Award. In 2004, she received the Grand Prize in the [[VSA arts]] Driving Force juried exhibition for emerging disabled artists.<ref>[http://www.vsarts.org/prebuilt/showcase/gallery/exhibits/vw/2004/index.html VSA Arts 2004 exhibition homepage] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061001192251/http://www.vsarts.org/prebuilt/showcase/gallery/exhibits/vw/2004/index.html |date=2006-10-01 }}, accessed on 2007-08-16</ref><ref>[http://www.vsarts.org/prebuilt/showcase/gallery/exhibits/vw/2004/s_taylor.html VSA Arts website for the 2004 winner] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070919215134/http://www.vsarts.org/prebuilt/showcase/gallery/exhibits/vw/2004/s_taylor.html |date=2007-09-19 }}, accessed on 2007-08-16</ref> A portion of her work deals with animal rights issues, as Taylor is an [[Abolitionism (animal rights)|abolitionist]] [[vegan]].<ref>[http://vegpage.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=8349:the-fallacy-of-conscientious-meat&catid=72:blogs-and-thoughts&Itemid=2 The Fallacy of Conscientious Meat], Sunaura and Alexander Taylor, accessed 21 February 2009</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thebaffler.com/latest/after-the-ugly-laws-taylor|title=After the Ugly Laws {{!}} Sunaura Taylor|date=2017-02-28|work=The Baffler|access-date=2018-07-10|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kalw.org/post/what-are-connections-between-animal-liberation-and-disability-liberation#stream/0|title=What are the connections between animal liberation and disability liberation?|last=Wenus|first=Rose Aguilar, Laura|access-date=2018-07-10|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/meatless-monday-the-art-of-the-animal-the-sexual_us_58a38d3ce4b0e172783aa1e9|title=Meatless Monday: The Art of the Animal -- The Sexual Politics of Meat Reframed|last=Kanner|first=Ellen|date=2017-02-27|website=Huffington Post|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-10}}</ref>
Taylor was born with [[arthrogryposis]], and uses a wheelchair. She is active in the Society for Disability Studies and has participated in marches for disability rights.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/persons-of-interest/are-disability-rights-and-animal-rights-connected|title=Are Disability Rights and Animal Rights Connected?|work=The New Yorker|access-date=2018-07-10|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://inthesetimes.com/article/20780/sunaura-taylor-beasts-of-burden-disability-justice-animal-liberation-vegan|title=How a Vegan’s Experience with Disability Is Helping Her Heal the Divide Between Two Movements|last=Vettese|first=Troy|date=2017-12-20|work=In These Times|access-date=2018-07-10|language=en-US|issn=0160-5992}}</ref> Her work on the disability rights movement has appeared in the Marxist magazine ''[[Monthly Review]]'',<ref>[http://www.monthlyreview.org/0304taylor.htm Monthly Review article] March 2004, accessed on 2007-08-16</ref> and her ''Self Portrait with TCE'' was the first full-color image ever printed in the publication's long history. She has been featured on ''[[All Things Considered]]'' on [[National Public Radio]],<ref>[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4520398 NPR program page]</ref> and the [[Georgia Public Television]] series ''State of the Arts''. Her work has also been featured frequently in ''[[Flagpole Magazine]]'' in her home town, [[Athens, Georgia]].
Taylor argued her position against animal products in her February 17, 2009 article titled "Is It Possible to Be a Conscientious Meat Eater?".<ref>http://www.alternet.org/story/127280/is_it_possible_to_be_a_conscientious_meat_eater AlterNet on ''Environment''</ref>
Taylor is also the sister of the filmmaker [[Astra Taylor]],<ref>http://www.freewilliamsburg.com/january_2002/sunny.html "Sunny Taylor", Free Williamsburg, accessed February 8, 2009.</ref> and appeared in her 2008 film ''[[Examined Life]]'' alongside philosopher [[Judith Butler]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sffs.org/events/films/film_examined_life.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-02-09 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523235557/http://www.sffs.org/events/films/film_examined_life.html |archivedate=2011-05-23 |df= }} San Francisco Film Society on ''Examined Life'', accessed February 8, 2009.</ref>
